>
	<p>
		I am a computer science student driven by a deep curiosity about how complex systems work
		and how they can be improved through technology. My work sits at the intersection of software
		engineering, data analysis, and financial systems. I spend much of my time building tools,
		experimenting with algorithms, and exploring how mathematical models can be used to make better
		decisions in uncertain environments.
	</p>

	<p>
		My primary programming language is Python, which I use to design analytical tools, automation systems, 
		and algorithmic trading models. I also work with C++-style environments through MetaTrader (MQL5) to 
		develop trading algorithms that analyze market structure, manage risk, and execute strategies with 
		minimal human intervention. Beyond trading systems, I explore data structures, algorithms, and system 
		design, always aiming to write code that is efficient, reliable, and adaptable.
	</p>

	<p>
		One of the areas I enjoy most is modeling real-world problems as computational systems. This includes 
		projects such as building simulators for operating system algorithms, developing automated trading bots, 
		and designing embedded systems like sensor-based monitoring solutions. These projects allow me to combine 
		theory with practical engineering.
	</p>

	<p>
		My long-term interest lies in quantitative systems and predictive modeling using mathematics, statistics, 
		and computing to understand markets, technology trends, and complex decision environments. I am particularly 
		interested in building systems that can analyze patterns, adapt to changing conditions, and operate autonomously.
	</p>

	
